classes.name: BswInternalBehavior
classes.note: Specifies the behavior of a BSW module or a BSW cluster w.r.t. the code entities visible by the BSW Scheduler. It is possible to have several different BswInternalBehaviors referring to the same BswModule Description.

arTypedPer.note: Defines an AUTOSAR typed memory-block that needs to available for each instance of the Basic Software The aggregation of arTypedPerInstanceMemory to variability with the purpose to support the Basic Software Module’s different algorithms in the requiring different number of memory atpVariation

bswPerInstance.note: Policy for a arTypedPerInstanceMemory The policy selects the options of the Schedule Manager API atpVariation 381 Document ID 89: AUTOSAR_CP_TPS_BSWModuleDescriptionTemplate Module Description Template R23-11

clientPolicy.note: Policy for a requiredClientServerEntry. The policy selects of the Schedule Manager API generation. atpVariation

distinguished.note: Indicates an abstract partition context in which the enclosing BswModuleEntity can be executed. atpVariation

entity.note: A code entity for which the behavior is described atpVariation

event.note: An event required by this module behavior. atpVariation

exclusiveArea.note: Policy for an ExclusiveArea in this BswInternalBehavior. The policy selects the options of the Schedule Manager atpVariation

includedData.note: The includedDataTypeSet is used by a basic software for its implementation.

includedMode.note: This aggregation represents the included Mode DeclarationGroups atpSplitable

internal.note: Policy for an internalTriggeringPoint in this BswInternal Behavior.. The policy selects the options of the Schedule API generation. atpVariation

modeReceiver.note: Implementation policy for the reception of mode switches. Stereotypes: atpSplitable; atpVariation

modeSender.note: Implementation policy for providing a mode group. atpSplitable; atpVariation

parameterPolicy.note: Policy for a perInstanceParameter in this BswInternal policy selects the options of the Schedule generation. atpVariation

perInstance.note: Describes a read only memory object containing characteristic value(s) needed by this BswInternal role name perInstanceParameter is chosen to the similar role in the context of SwcInternal to constantMemory, this object is not allocated the module’s code, but by the BSW Scheduler is accessed from the BSW module via the BSW The main use case is the support of of calibration data. is subject to variability with the purpose implementation variants. atpVariation

receptionPolicy.note: Data reception policy for inter-partition and/or inter-core atpVariation 381 Document ID 89: AUTOSAR_CP_TPS_BSWModuleDescriptionTemplate Module Description Template R23-11

releasedTrigger.note: Policy for a releasedTrigger. The policy selects the options of the Schedule Manager API generation. atpVariation

schedulerName.note: Optional definition of one or more prefixes to be used for the BswScheduler. atpVariation

sendPolicy.note: Policy for a providedData. The policy selects the options Schedule Manager API generation. atpVariation

service.note: Defines the requirements on AUTOSAR Services for a particular item. is subject to variability with the purpose the conditional existence of ServiceNeeds. is splitable in order to support that be provided in later development atpVariation

triggerDirect.note: Specifies a trigger to be directly implemented via OS calls. atpVariation

variationPoint.note: Proxy of a variation points in the C/C++ implementation. atpSplitable

classes.name: BswModuleEntity
classes.note: Specifies the smallest code fragment which can be described for a BSW module or cluster within AUTOSAR.

accessedMode.note: A mode group which is accessed via API call by this entity. It shall be a ModeDeclarationGroupPrototype this module or cluster. atpVariation

activationPoint.note: Activation point used by the module entity to activate one more internal triggers. atpVariation

callPoint.note: A call point used in the code of this entity. of this association is especially targeted at It is possible to have one variant calling AUTOSAR debug module and another one which atpVariation

dataReceive.note: The data is received via the BSW Scheduler. atpSplitable; atpVariation

dataSendPoint.note: The data is sent via the BSW Scheduler. atpVariation

implemented.note: The entry which is implemented by this module entity.

issuedTrigger.note: A trigger issued by this entity via BSW Scheduler API call. be a BswTrigger released (i.e. owned) by this cluster. atpVariation 381 Document ID 89: AUTOSAR_CP_TPS_BSWModuleDescriptionTemplate Module Description Template R23-11

managedMode.note: A mode group which is managed by this entity. It shall be a ModeDeclarationGroupPrototype provided by this cluster. atpVariation

schedulerName.note: A prefix to be used in generated names for the Bsw ModuleScheduler in the context of this BswModuleEntity, entry point prototypes, macros for dealing areas, header file names. defined in the SWS RTE. supersedes default rules for the prefix of those

classes.name: BswCalledEntity
classes.note: BSW module entity which is designed to be called from another BSW module or cluster.

classes.name: BswSchedulableEntity
classes.note: BSW module entity, which is designed for control by the BSW Scheduler. It may for example implement a so-called "main" function.

classes.name: BswInterruptEntity
classes.note: BSW module entity, which is designed to be triggered by an interrupt.

interruptSource.note: Allows a textual documentation of the intended interrupt

classes.name: BswModuleCallPoint
classes.note: Represents a point at which a BswModuleEntity handles a procedure call into a BswModuleEntry, either directly or via the BSW Scheduler.

context.note: The existence of this reference indicates that the call point is used only in the context of the referred Bsw

classes.name: BswDirectCallPoint
classes.note: Represents a concrete point in the code from where a BswModuleEntry is called directly, i.e. not via the BSW Scheduler. This information can be used to analyze call tree and resource locking scenarios. It is not needed to configure the BSW Scheduler.

calledEntry.note: The BswModuleEntry called at this point.

calledFrom.note: This indicates that the call point is located at the deepest level inside one or more ExclusiveAreas that are nested the given order.

classes.name: BswSynchronousServerCallPoint
classes.note: Represents a synchronous procedure call point via the BSW Scheduler.

calledFrom.note: This indicates that the call point is located at the deepest level inside one or more ExclusiveAreas that are nested the given order.

classes.name: BswAsynchronousServerCallPoint
classes.note: Represents an asynchronous procedure call point via the BSW Scheduler.

classes.name: BswAsynchronousServerCallResultPoint
classes.note: The callback point for an BswAsynchronousServerCallPoint i.e. the point at which the result can be retrieved from the BSW Scheduler.

asynchronous.note: The call point invoking the call to which the result belongs.

classes.name: BswVariableAccess
classes.note: The presence of a BswVariableAccess implies that a BswModuleEntity needs access to a VariableData Prototype via the BSW Scheduler. The kind of access is specified by the role in which the class is used.

accessedVariable.note: The data accessed via the BSW Scheduler.

context.note: The existence of this reference indicates that the variable is received resp. sent only in the context of the referred

classes.name: BswExclusiveAreaPolicy
classes.note: The ExclusiveArea for which the BSW Scheduler using this policy.

apiPrinciple.note: Specifies for this ExclusiveArea if either one common set and Exit APIs for the whole BSW module is the SchM or if the set of Enter and Exit expected per BswModuleEntity. The default value

exclusiveArea.note: The ExclusiveArea for which the BSW Scheduler using

classes.name: BswSchedulerNamePrefix
classes.note: A prefix to be used in names of generated code artifacts which make up the interface of a BSW module to the BswScheduler.

classes.name: BswEvent
classes.note: Base class of various kinds of events which are used to trigger a BswModuleEntity of this BSW module or cluster. The event is local to the BSW module or cluster. The short name of the meta-class instance is intended as an input to configure the required API of the BSW Scheduler.

context.note: The existence of this reference indicates that the usage of the event is limited to the context of the referred Bsw

startsOnEvent.note: The entity which is started by the event.

classes.name: BswScheduleEvent
classes.note: BswEvent that is able to start a BswSchedulabeEntity.

classes.name: BswInterruptEvent
classes.note: This meta-class represents an event triggered by an interrupt.

classes.name: BswTimingEvent
classes.note: A recurring BswEvent driven by a time period.

period.note: Requirement for the time period (in seconds) by which is triggered.

classes.name: BswBackgroundEvent
classes.note: A recurring BswEvent which is used to perform background activities. It is similar to a BswTimingEvent but has no fixed time period and is activated only with low priority.

classes.name: BswOsTaskExecutionEvent
classes.note: This BswEvent is supposed to execute BswSchedulableEntitys which have to react on the execution of specific OsTasks. Therefore, this event is unconditionally raised whenever the OsTask on which it is mapped is executed. The main use case for this event is scheduling of Runnables of Complex Drivers which have to react on task executions.

classes.name: BswInternalTriggeringPoint
classes.note: Represents the activation point for one or more BswInternalTriggerOccurredEvents.

swImplPolicy.note: This attribute, when set to value queued, specifies a of the internal trigger event.

classes.name: BswInternalTriggerOccurredEvent
classes.note: A BswEvent, which can happen sporadically. The event is activated by explicit calls from the module to the BSW Scheduler. The main purpose for such an event is to cause a context switch, e.g. from an ISR context into a task context. Activation and switching are handled within the same module or cluster only.

eventSourcePoint.note: The activation point is the source of this event.

classes.name: BswExternalTriggerOccurredEvent
classes.note: A BswEvent resulting from a trigger released by another module or cluster.

trigger.note: The trigger associated with this event. The trigger is this module.

classes.name: BswModeSwitchEvent
classes.note: A BswEvent resulting from a mode switch.

activation.note: Kind of activation w.r.t. to the referred mode. ModeDeclaration 0..2 iref Reference to one or two Modes that initiate the Mode by: ModeInBswModule

classes.name: BswModeSwitchedAckEvent
classes.note: The event is raised after a switch of the referenced mode group has been acknowledged or an error occurs. The referenced mode group shall be provided by this module.

modeGroup.note: A mode group provided by this module. The of a switch of this group raises this

classes.name: BswModeManagerErrorEvent
classes.note: This represents the ability to react on errors occurring during mode handling.

modeGroup.note: This represents the ModeDeclarationGroupPrototype for the error behavior of the mode manager applies.

classes.name: BswOperationInvokedEvent
classes.note: this event is not needed in case of direct function calls.

entry.note: The providedClientServerEntry invoked by this event.

classes.name: BswAsynchronousServerCallReturnsEvent
classes.note: This is the "callback" event for asynchronous Client-Server-Communication via the BSW Scheduler which is thrown after completion of the asynchronous Client-Server call. Its eventSource specifies the call point to be used for retrieving the result.

eventSource.note: The call point to be used for retrieving the result.

classes.name: BswDataReceivedEvent
classes.note: This event is thrown on reception of the referenced data via Sender-Receiver-Communication over the BSW Scheduler.

classes.name: BswTriggerDirectImplementation
classes.note: Specifies a released trigger to be directly implemented via OS calls, for example in a Complex Driver module.

cat2Isr.note: The name of the OS category 2 ISR, which is controlled referred trigger. This means, that the module category 2 ISR (e.g. according hardware enabling of ISR). Instead of calling an SchM API to raise the appropriate events in modules receiving the trigger, this ISR the triggered ExecutableEntitys. The is required by the integrator to map the Bsw RTEEvents to this ISR.

masteredTrigger.note: The trigger which is directly mastered by this module. be several different BswTriggerDirect the same Trigger. This may e.g. due to memory partitioning.

task.note: The name of the OS task, which is controlled by the This means, that the module uses the to directly activate an OS task instead of API of the BswScheduler. The task name is the RTE generator resp. BswScheduler to appropriate events in components or modules trigger.

classes.name: BswModeSenderPolicy
classes.note: Specifies the details for the sending of a mode switch for the referred mode group.

enhancedMode.note: This controls the creation of the enhanced mode API that information about the previous mode and the next set to TRUE the enhanced mode API is be generated. For more details please refer SWS_RTE.

providedMode.note: The provided mode group for which the policy is specified. 381 Document ID 89: AUTOSAR_CP_TPS_BSWModuleDescriptionTemplate Module Description Template R23-11

queueLength.note: Length of call queue on the sender side. The queue is the RTE resp.BswScheduler. The value greater or equal to 0. Setting the value of queue 0 implies non-queued communication.

classes.name: BswModeSwitchAckRequest
classes.note: Requests acknowledgements that a mode switch has been processed successfully

timeout.note: Number of seconds before an error is reported.

classes.name: BswModeReceiverPolicy
classes.note: Specifies the details for the reception of a mode switch for the referred mode group.

enhancedMode.note: This controls the creation of the enhanced mode API that information about the previous mode and the next set to TRUE the enhanced mode API is be generated. For more details please refer SWS_RTE.

requiredMode.note: The required mode group for which the policy is specified.

supports.note: Specifies whether the module can handle the reception of asynchronous mode switch (true) or not (false).

classes.name: BswDataReceptionPolicy
classes.note: Specifies the reception policy for the referred data in sender-receiver communication over the BSW Scheduler. To be used for inter-partition and/or inter-core communication.

receivedData.note: The data received over the BSW Scheduler using this

classes.name: BswQueuedDataReceptionPolicy
classes.note: Reception policy attributes specific for queued receiving.

queueLength.note: Length of queue for received events.

classes.name: BswDistinguishedPartition
classes.note: Each instance of this meta-class represents an abstract partition in which context the code of the enclosing BswModuleBehavior can be executed. The intended use case is to distinguish between several partitions in order to implement different behavior per partition, for example to behave either as a master or satellite in a multicore ECU with shared BSW code.

classes.name: BswServiceDependency
classes.note: Specialization of ServiceDependency in the context of an BswInternalBehavior. It allows to associate BswModuleEntries and data defined for a BSW module or cluster to a given ServiceNeeds element.

assignedData.note: Defines the role of an associated data object (owned by module or cluster) in the context of the ServiceNeeds atpVariation

assignedEntry.note: Defines the role of an associated BswModuleEntry in the context of the ServiceNeeds element. atpVariation

ident.note: This adds the ability to become referrable to BswService

classes.name: RoleBasedBswModuleEntryAssignment
classes.note: This class specifies an assignment of a role to a particular BswModuleEntry (usually a configurable callback). With this assignment, the role of the callback is mapped to a specific ServiceNeeds element, so that a tool is able to create appropriate configuration values for the module that implements the AUTOSAR Service.
